Gaussian Blur¶

It is a widely used effect in graphics software, typically to reduce image noise and reduce detail.

The visual effect of this blurring technique is a smooth blur resembling that of viewing the image through a translucent screen.

Why do it ?¶

Edge detection¶

Gaussian smoothing is commonly used with edge detection. Most edge-detection algorithms are sensitive to noise; the 2-D Laplacian filter, built from a discretization of the Laplace operator, is highly sensitive to noisy environments.

Using a Gaussian Blur filter before edge detection aims to reduce the level of noise in the image, which improves the result of the following edge-detection algorithm. This approach is commonly referred to as Laplacian of Gaussian, or LoG filtering.

Photography¶

Lower-end digital cameras, including many mobile phone cameras, commonly use gaussian blurring to cover up image noise caused by higher ISO light sensitivities.

Gaussian blur automatically is applied as part of the image post-processing of the photo by the camera software, leading to an irrevesible loss of deta

Making our own kernel¶

Let's get to the filter part.

Imagine the kernel as a matrix of size n x n

To make our own gaussian filter the approach is going to be

  • Use np.random.multivariate_normal to sample points with specific mean and covaraince matrices
  • The mean would depend on the size of the kernel that we want and would be at the center of the kernel.
  • Once we have our points in the 2D space we will do an accumulation to see how many points lie in each of the box of the matrix and summing that would give us the value for each of the box

For example in the 8x8 grid below we have filled the random normal points. As one would expect the points have higher density in the center and become sparser away from the center i.e 4,4

Now when we count the points , box (0,1) has one point , (0,5) has 2 and so on.

def updateKernel(kernel,i):
    i,j = list(i)
    kernel[i,j] += 1
    return kernel

Applying the Kernel to the Image¶

Now we have our filter and the image. Let's put the two together.

We could use scipy's convolve2d but that would be too easy. And more importantly we won't know how it works.

SO how it works is..

Take the kernel/filter and move it across the image. source

Here the blue grid is the image, green is the output and the grey thing moving is the kernel.

In the code below, a trick is employed. Instead of looping over and computing the cross convolution. We loop over only to collect the patches and then broadcast to compute the cross convolution.

In [504]:
def apply_filter(im , kernel):
    ih = im.shape[0]
    iw = im.shape[1]
    kh = kernel.shape[0]
    kw = kernel.shape[1]
    
    outimg = np.zeros((ih-kh+1 , iw-kw+1))
    patches = []
    
    for index, val in np.ndenumerate(outimg):
        i,j = index
        patch = im[i:i+kh , j:j+kw]
        patches.append(patch)
    
    patches = np.dstack(patches)
    return np.sum(np.multiply(patches , kernel.reshape(kh,kw,1)) , axis=(0,1)).reshape(outimg.shape[0],outimg.shape[1])

Making things interactive¶

okay now we got our filter applied to the image. But how about if we change the kernel size ? What happens then ?

Let's make things interactive using ipywidgets! Play around with the slider and look for yourself.

In [511]:
def kernel_play(im,showFunc , size=9):
    #def applyFilter(meana , meanb):
    kernel_n = size
    cells = [i for i in range(kernel_n)]
    middle = kernel_n//2
    gaussian_kernel = np.random.multivariate_normal([middle,middle] , [[middle/4,0], [0,middle/4]] , 10000)
    kernel = np.zeros((kernel_n , kernel_n))
    for i in np.floor(gaussian_kernel).astype(int):
        kernel = updateKernel(kernel,i)
    #_= [updateKernel(i) for i in np.round(gaussian_kernel).astype(int)]
    im = apply_filter(im, kernel)
    showFunc(im)

def imToSurface(im):
    X = np.arange(0, im.shape[1], 1)
    Y = np.arange(0, im.shape[0], 1)
    X,Y = np.meshgrid(X, Y)
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,6))
    ax = fig.add_subplot(1,2,1, projection='3d')
    ax.plot_surface(X,Y,im, cmap=cm.coolwarm)
    
    ax2 = fig.add_subplot(1,2,2)
    ax2.imshow(im , cmap='gray')
    plt.show();
